-- 
Crude Oil Volatility Rises to Six-Week High as Futures Fluctuate

-- B y   M a r g o t   H a b i b y
-- 
2011-09-26T18:26:08Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-26/crude-oil-volatility-rises-to-six-week-high-as-futures-fluctuate.html
Oil options volatility surged to
the highest level in six weeks as the underlying futures touched
the lowest intraday price since Aug. 9.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
November, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a
gauge of options prices, was 49.9 percent at 1:54 p.m. in  New
York , the highest level for the contract nearest to expiration
since Aug. 9. Volatility was up from 48.6 percent Sept. 23 and
42 percent a week ago.  Oil for November delivery increased 78 cents, or 1 percent,
to $80.63 a barrel at 1:53 p.m. on the  New York Mercantile
Exchange . Earlier, futures touched $77.11 a barrel. Oil has
dropped 9.4 percent this month and 16 percent in the third
quarter.  The most active contract in electronic trading today was
December $100 calls, with 1,696 lots changing hands. The options
slipped 1 cent to 55 cents a barrel. December $80 puts, the
next-most-active options, fell 41 cents to $5.62 a barrel on
volume of 1,348. One contract covers 1,000 barrels of crude.  The volume of puts outnumbered calls by 56 percent to 44
percent in electronic trading.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information on floor trading, where the
bulk of options trading occur the next business day.  November $100 calls were the most active options traded in
the previous session, with 5,402 lots changing hands. They fell
2 cents to 10 cents a barrel. The next-most active options,
December $80 puts, increased 30 cents to $6.03 a barrel on
volume of 5,000.  Open interest was highest for December $100 calls with
52,843 contracts. Next were December $50 puts with 45,538 and
December $70 puts with 44,409.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Margot Habiby in Dallas at 
